<br>
I like my 61+ draughts.  They are good for speed and damage output.  The only thing about them that could be improved really is their mana ratio.  Sure, focus items are nice, but they have a hard cap, and are not exactly trivial to get.  Also, any class character can get focus items.<br>
<br>
I was just noticing how the sustained damage output of enchanters, magicians, and necromancers in PoP can be quite a lot.  Wizards can put out a bit of damage too, but out mana bar suffers greatly.  If you don't know what I'm talking about, watch an enchanter with Command of Druzzil in Bastion of Thunder.  My goodness what damage they can do.  (This is a good thing, mind you)<br>
<br>
If you take an enchanter to BoT, and calculate his/her damage per mana when considering charm recasts etc., you will have a baseline value for enchanters.  Do the same for magicians and necromancers in their respective abilities.  Once you have this data, you can check wizard balance among them.<br>
<br>
I have never done this experiment, so I don't have any hard data to provide, but I have a feeling wizards might be slightly disadvantaged in this area.  (I said &quot;a feeling&quot;, but it's up to the dev team or whoever to really check it out)<br>
<br>
What do I propose?<br>
<br>
Increase our spell damage?  No.<br>
Increase our spell ratios?  No.<br>
Give us pointy hats?  Maybe.<br>
<br>
Seriously though, I propose the following wizard spell:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Focus of the Arcanist:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Level: 64 (because that's the level of CoD)<br>
Mana: 175 (1/4 the cost of CoD with 1/4 the duration)<br>
Duration: 2 minutes (with the ability to break randomly like charm)<br>
Effect: This is somewhat complicated, but basically would be similar to some necromancer spells that put an effect on the MOB and an effect on the caster (like the STR stealer thing) that wears off both at the same time.<br>
<br>
The actual effect could do anything from decreasing the mana cost of our DD spells cast on that MOB only by whatever percentage makes sense, decreasing the cast time of our spells against that MOB, or whatever.  Whenever the spell breaks/wears off the MOB, the effect comes off us.<br>
<br>
<br>
Basically, this is sort of an &quot;innate focus&quot; similar to Iceflame of E'ci, but also works similarly to charm/mark of karn/etc. in that you have to land it on the MOB you want to attack.  It also would not really increase the damage of our spells necessarily.  It could simply make us be very fast/efficient against that one MOB for the duration of the spell.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hypothetical randomly made up example:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Suppose an enchanter charms a MOB that puts out 600 dps.  Also suppose that the charm spell lasts for 7 minutes 30 seconds for a cost of 700 mana.  Well, over the course of those 450 seconds, the enchanter can dish out a maximum of 270000 damage at a ratio of 385 damage per mana.<br>
<br>
Well, assuming that charm can break randomly, let us suppose that the charm lasts for only half the max duration over the average course, and possibly gets resisted at least one cast.  That brings it to 135000 damage in 3 minutes 45 seconds for 1400 mana, giving 96 damage per mana.<br>
<br>
If your look at our 62+ draught spells, they are 955 damage for 255 mana @ 3 seconds per cast.  That gives 318 dps @ 3.75 damage per mana.  At a full burn, a wizard with 4000 mana will be OOM in roughly 54 seconds after 18 casts for a total of 17190 damage.  Adding in mana regen figures, a wizard can roughly regen a total of 1875 mana in 3.75 minutes for an additional 7640 damage.  That's 24830 damage versus 135000.  If the enchanter figures were real, that would show a bit of an imbalance in that situation.<br>
<br>
If our &quot;Focus of the Arcanist&quot; spell cut spell mana cost by 75%, and cust spell cast time by 50%, then how would we fare?<br>
<br>
* 175 mana for FotA + 175 more for a resist = 300 mana, leaving 3700 mana to work with for 2 minutes. <br>
* 2 minutes regens roughly 1000 mana, giving a total of 4700 mana to dish out damage.<br>
* 255 - 10% (specialization) - 75% (FotA) = 38.25 mana per cast<br>
* 3 second cast * 50% = 1.5 seconds per cast<br>
* 120 seconds / 1.5 seconds = 80 maximum possible casts (based on time)<br>
* 80 casts * 38.25 mana = 3060 mana used<br>
* 80 casts * 955 damage = 76400 maximum total damage in 2 minutes.<br>
<br>
If you adjust these values based on the 3.75 minute average charm time for the enchanter, it gives us 143250 maximum possible damage to their <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>average</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 135000 total damage.<br>
<br>
I'm thinking the spell would need to have a major aggro-reducing component to it like Spell Casting Subtlety (but only for the MOB it is on)<br>
<br>
Again, these values (other than spell data) are purely hypothetical, and pulled out of the air.  I don't know if this type of spell would be good or not, but I just thought it sounded neat when I thought of it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Disclaimer:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
1) This is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> an &quot;enchanter ability&quot; area, because it is simply the wizard focusing his magic on one specific target.  This could have been designed as a &quot;discipline&quot;, but I don't think the engine would support it, due to its need to be resistable and wear off.<br>
<br>
2) These values are just random possibilities that would most definitely have to be tuned under test.<br>
<br>
3) I do not want a farking pet to do my damage.  I just want to be able to keep up with those who DO have pets to do their damage.<br>
<br>
4) This would have very little impact on wizard soloing, other than slightly increasing the total damage we can do.  Currently, any MOB that doesn't summon can pretty much be killed solo by a wizard with a decent mana pool.  This would just make us have less downtime.  (e.g. druids/shamans who root/DoT/med)  I see no big deal in this area.<br>
<br>
5) This does not significantly increase our total damage output, except over extended durations.  All the time values and the like can be tweaked anyway.  Most PoP battles only last a few minutes too.  You also have to factor in possible resists, and the fact that they could limit this to what spells it affects.<br>
<br>
Ok.  Fire away.  Do you think this has potential, or not? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cedrich>Cedrich</A> at: 1/1/03 1:59:26 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=onnatop>Onnatop</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 381<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/1/03 2:43 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Another spell idea...</span><hr size=1> That's a really good idea, I have to admit. I have some numbers, not done by myself, but from what a friend of mine says who uses charmed pets in Crypt of Decay. He said his pet WITH mage items (muzzle, swords, etc...) can get up to 203 DPS from one pet. Mind you, this is DIRE charmed pets in CoD (so, little lower level). He can get up to around 600 DPS with his druid dire, chanter dire and his warrior (damn insane multi-boxers). Command of Druzzil charmed pets will certainly do more damage than that, as you can grab much higher level mobs.<br>
