<br>
What I was trying to do was invent &quot;wizard charm&quot; (i.e. the wizard equivalent of charm)<br>
<br>
I wanted an ability that had similar advantages and disadvantages to charm.  Possibly the spell could generate huge aggro toward the wizard when it breaks, just like when a charmed MOB turns on its master after charm breaks.  We would have to recast our focus spell to remove aggro again.  There are so many possibilities.<br>
<br>
I just do not see an &quot;across the board&quot; change to our damage output ability.  This would be very unbalancing.  (e.g. take a level 65 enchanter to Blackburrow with CoD.  He/she isn't gonna be dishing out 600dps there.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=claudshadowflare>ClaudShadowflare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Has Eddie Murphy's<BR>taste in women</span><br>  Posts: 1847<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/1/03 7:36 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I agree</span><hr size=1> So you're envious of a chanter ability.  You design a spell after a highly praised enchanter spell.  You cite chanters endlessly in your first post.<br>
